properties.Title: Tropical Cyclone Information Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: For Post-tropical Storm Dorian. The next intermediate statement will be issued at 12:00 a.m. ADT. Followed by the full information statement issued at 03:00 a.m. ADT. The center of Post-Tropical cyclone Dorian made landfall just southwest of Halifax earlier this evening. Dorian will continue to track across the Maritimes with destructive winds and heavy rainfall this evening. 1. Summary of basic information at 09:00 p.m. ADT. Location: Near 45.0 North 63.2 West. About: 48 kilometres north-northeast of Halifax. Maximum sustained winds: 148 kilometres per hour. Present movement: northeast at 47 kilometres per hour. Minimum central pressure: 958 millibars. 2. Public weather impacts and warnings summary. Dorian made landfall over the Chebucto Peninsula of Nova Scotia (southwest of Halifax) between Terence Bay and Sambro at approximately 7:15 pm this evening. The center of the storm will continue tracking northeastward tonight, passing near eastern Prince Edward Island around midnight, and then over the eastern Gulf of St. Lawrence waters or western Newfoundland by Sunday morning. Severe winds and torrential rain will continue to impact parts of Nova Scotia, southeastern New Brunswick, Prince Edward Island, Western Newfoundland, the Magdalen Islands and the Quebec's Lower North Shore tonight. Large waves are expected for the Atlantic coasts of Nova Scotia, Newfoundland and for eastern portions of the Gulf of St. Lawrence tonight. Finally, storm surge, combined with large waves and pounding surf, may give flooding for parts of eastern Nova Scotia, Prince Edward Island, Newfoundland, the Magdalen Islands, and parts of the Quebec's Lower North Shore. Hurricane warnings are in effect for the south shore, central and eastern Nova Scotia and western Newfoundland. Hurricane Watches are in effect for eastern Prince Edward Island, and the Magdalen Islands. Tropical storm warnings are in effect for southeastern New Brunswick, Prince Edward Island, western and northern Nova Scotia, parts of northern and southwestern Newfoundland, the Magdalen Islands and parts of Quebec's Lower North Shore. a. Wind. Wind gusts up to 140 km/h were reported near Halifax earlier this afternoon in the easterly winds ahead of Dorian's approach. Yarmouth airport reported a wind gust of 130 km/h hour in the strengthening northwest winds behind Dorian. Much of the region will continue to be impacted by severe and damaging winds tonight. Damaging east to northeasterly winds will continue ahead of Dorian's track tonight, with severe and damaging northwesterly winds developing in its wake. Wind impacts will likely be enhanced by foliage on the trees, causing broken branches and tree falls, widespread power outages, blocking of roads, and other type of damages. b. Rainfall. Several reporting stations in western Nova Scotia and southeastern New Brunswick have already received in excess of 100 mm of as of early this evening. Rainfall warnings have been ended for the southwestern corner of Nova Scotia, from Yarmouth to Halifax. Rainfall warning remain in effect for the remainder of Nova Scotia, western Prince Edward Island, most of New Brunswick stretching from the southwest towards the Gaspesie, and parts of the Lower North Shore Quebec. Widespread rainfall amounts of 50 to 100 mm are expected over Nova Scotia, Prince Edward Island, and the Magdalen Islands. Maximum amounts are likely over western Nova Scotia where 100 to 200 mm are possible. These amounts and rainfall rates could easily give rise to road washouts and localized flash flooding. c. Surge/Waves. Storm surge warnings have been ended for southwestern Nova Scotia including Halifax, but remain in effect for most of the Atlantic coast of Nova Scotia, the north shore of Prince Edward Island, western Cape Breton, portions of southwestern Newfoundland, the Magdalen Islands, Quebec's Lower Quebec North Shore, and Anticosti Island. For eastern Nova Scotia high waves and storm surge may cause flooding for some low lying coastal areas tonight. For the southwestern Newfoundland and areas along the Gulf of Saint Lawrence localized flooding due to storm surge and high waves are likely during high tide tonight. There will also be rough and pounding surf, especially for parts of Nova Scotia, Newfoundland and the Gulf of St. Lawrence tonight. Waves of 7 to 10 metres are reaching the southwestern shore of Nova Scotia this evening and will reach Eastern Shore tonight. These waves will likely reach southern Newfoundland by Sunday morning with waves nearing 12 metres. Waves of 4 to 7 metres will impact north facing coasts of the Gulf of St. Lawrence. Note that waves will break higher along some of the coastlines, and dangerous rip currents are likely. Please exercise extreme caution. 3. Marine weather impacts and warnings summary. Hurricane force wind warnings are in effect for most Atlantic waters, storm warnings are in effect for other waters in the Maritimes. For Newfoundland, hurricane force wind warnings are in effect for eastern Gulf of St. Lawrence waters, storm force warnings for the southwest and northeast coasts, and the strait of Belle Isle. Gale warnings are in effect for the remaining waters. Significant wave heights of 10 to 15 metres are expected in offshore waters south of Nova Scotia this evening, and waters south of Newfoundland later tonight into Sunday morning. As the low continues east Sunday into Monday, waves of 4 to 7 metres will develop over eastern waters, and for the southwestern Grand Banks will build to 5 to 10 metres. Forecasters: Borgel/Hatt ### Please continue to monitor alerts issued by the Canadian Hurricane Centre and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.

properties.Title: High Water Level Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Higher than normal water levels are expected or occurring. Post-tropical storm Dorian will move into the southern Gulf of St. Lawrence tonight and northern Gulf of St. Lawrence on Sunday morning. Dorian will bring strong easterly then westerly winds, which will create large waves and combine with storm surge to give higher than normal water levels at high tide tonight and Sunday morning. ### Coastal flooding is likely. Coastal erosion is possible in vulnerable areas. High water level warnings are issued when water levels pose a threat to coastal regions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. For more information monitor Canadian Coast Guard radio or Weatheradio stations.

properties.Title: Storm Surge Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: High Storm Surge levels and large waves are expected to impact the coast. The intense winds associated with now post-tropical storm Dorian are forecast to generate large waves and storm surge for parts of the Gulf of St. Lawrence and the eastern shore of Nova Scotia. For the eastern shore of Nova Scotia, high waves and storm surge may cause flooding for some low lying coastal areas over the next couple of hours. For the Gulf of St. Lawrence localized flooding due to storm surge and high waves are likely during high tide tonight. ### Coastal flooding is possible along the shoreline. Storm surge warnings are issued when water levels pose a threat to coastal regions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to PEstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #PEStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Higher than normal water levels are expected or occurring. High waves and pounding surf will begin to affect the southwest coast of Newfoundland overnight as Post Tropical Cyclone Dorian passes to the west. These conditions, combined with elevated water levels, may result in coastal flooding and damage to infrastructure, especially at high tide near dawn on Sunday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. For more information monitor Canadian Coast Guard radio or Weatheradio stations.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. Heavy rain associated with now post-tropical storm Dorian will taper off overnight tonight or early Sunday morning. Rainfall amounts of 50 to 100 mm have already fallen with possibly higher amounts locally, especially over southeastern New Brunswick. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.
